<h2 id=3D"hexagon-definition">Hexagon definition</h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/hexagon.png"=
 alt=3D""></p>
<p>A <strong>hexagon</strong> is a shape with six sides and six angles.</p>
<p>The most common type of hexagon, and the one that we will talk about bel=
ow, is the <strong>regular hexagon</strong>, which is a special type of pol=
ygon. This is because all sides of a regular hexagon have the same length a=
nd all angles have the same measure.</p>
<p>Hexagons are often found in nature, such as in the shapes of honeycomb c=
ells, and in various fields such as mathematics, architecture, and design.<=
/p>
<p>For regular hexagons, the following properties apply:</p>
<ul>
<li>All sides are equal in length.</li>
<li>All interior angles measure 120=C2=B0.</li>
<li>All exterior angles measure 60=C2=B0.</li>
<li>It can be divided into six equilateral triangles.</li>
<li>The opposite sides are parallel to each other.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"parts-of-a-hexagon">Parts of a hexagon</h2>
<p>The five parts of a regular hexagon mentioned in this tool are: side len=
gth (a), area (A), perimeter (P), apothem (r) and circumradius (R).</p>
<h3 id=3D"side-length-a">Side length (a)</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/side-length.=
png" alt=3D""></p>
<p>The <strong>side length</strong> of a regular hexagon is a measure of th=
e distance from one vertex to another along one of the sides.</p>
<p>It can be calculated using the following formulas:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>If you know the perimeter of the hexagon:</p>
<p><code>a =3D P / 6</code></p></li>
<li><p>If you know the apothem:</p>
<p><code>a =3D 2 * r / =E2=88=9A(3)</code></p></li>
<li><p>If you know the area:</p>
<p><code>a =3D =E2=88=9A(2 * A / 3 / =E2=88=9A(3))</code></p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"area-a">Area (A)</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/area.png" al=
t=3D""></p>
<p>The <strong>area</strong> of a regular hexagon is a measure of the size =
of the hexagonal region it encloses.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>The formula for calculating the area of a polygon is always the same=
, no matter how many sides it has, as long as it is a <strong>regular polyg=
on</strong>:</p>
<p><code>A =3D r * P / 2</code></p></li>
<li><p>If you know only the side length of the hexagon, you can still find =
the area, using the following formula:</p>
<p><code>A =3D 3 * =E2=88=9A(3) / 2 * a=C2=B2</code></p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"perimeter-p">Perimeter (P)</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/perimeter.pn=
g" alt=3D""></p>
<p>The <strong>perimeter</strong> of a regular hexagon is a measure of the =
total distance around the hexagonal shape.</p>
<p>The formula for calculating the perimeter of a regular hexagon is:</p>
<p><code>P =3D 6 * a</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"apothem-r">Apothem (r)</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/apothem.png"=
 alt=3D""></p>
<p>The <strong>apothem</strong> of a regular hexagon is a line segment that=
 runs from the center of the hexagon to the midpoint of one of its sides.</=
p>
<p>The formula for calculating the apothem is:</p>
<p><code>r =3D a * =E2=88=9A(3) / 2</code></p>
<h3 id=3D"circumradius-r">Circumradius (R)</h3>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/circumradius=
.png" alt=3D""></p>
<p>The <strong>circumradius</strong> of a regular hexagon is the distance f=
rom the center of the hexagon to one of its vertices.</p>
<p>In the case of a regular hexagon, it is simply equal to the side length.=
</p>
<p><code>R =3D a</code></p>
<h2 id=3D"types-of-hexagons">Types of hexagons</h2>
<p><img src=3D"https://calckit.io/tool_assets/geometry/hexagon/types-of-hex=
agons.png" alt=3D""></p>
<p>Hexagons can be divided into various categories based on the measurement=
s of their sides and angles.</p>
<p>Based on their sides, they can be classified as:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Regular hexagons</strong>, when the length of all the sides =
and measure of all the angles are equal.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Irregular hexagons</strong>, when the length of sides and me=
asure of angles do not have the same measure.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Based on their angles, they can be classified as:</p>
<ul>
<li><p><strong>Convex hexagons</strong>, when all of the interior angles ar=
e less than 180 degrees, and all the vertices are pointed outwards. Convex =
hexagons can be regular or irregular.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Concave hexagons</strong>, when at least one of the interior=
 angles is greater than 180=C2=B0 and at least one vertex points inwards. C=
oncave hexagons are always irregular.</p></li>
</ul></div>
